The western margin of the third commercial ring opens at Cedar Square, where older stone construction speaks to the neighborhood's pre-Lantern Reform origins. A carved milestone embedded in the corner pavement records distances to the principal markets and civic offices, updated during the last cadastral survey. Gate wardens maintain a checkpoint at the end of the block, their kiosk decorated with posted travel advisories for the commercial routes. The architecture transitions here from the inner ring's finished civic stonework to the heavier, plainer construction of the outer residential quarter.

