The fifth ring of Cedar Square has shed most of its commercial identity, the cedar-framed buildings converted to tenement housing whose ground floors serve as storage for the rope-makers and barrel-coopers who work in the western industrial quarter. The street is quieter here, the foot traffic limited to residents and delivery carts, and a worn sandstone step at one doorway has been hollowed into a natural seat where neighbours gather to talk in the evening lamplight.

